            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mateo Solis\u2019s life is a study in structure, a reflection of the digital frameworks he designs. The son of Filipino immigrants, he was raised in the fog-drenched suburbs of Daly City. His name, a legacy of Spanish colonialism in the Philippines, was a frequent point of curiosity. His father, a stoic auto mechanic, and his mother, a compassionate caregiver, instilled in him a profound work ethic and a quiet sense of duty. They envisioned a stable, practical future for their son, a world away from their own laborious lives.\n\nInitially, Mateo pursued this path, enrolling in library science. He loved the logic of cataloging and the calm of the stacks. However, the first dot-com boom of the late 90s ignited a different passion. He saw a new frontier of information that wasn't bound by paper, and pivoted, earning a graduate degree from UC Berkeley\u2019s prestigious School of Information. His career ascended steadily, his talent for bringing order to digital chaos making him an invaluable asset. Now a Principal Information Architect at a major tech firm, he designs the invisible scaffolding that supports massive data systems.\n\nA significant turning point was his divorce a decade ago. It was amicable but altering, a system failure in his personal life that he couldn\u2019t architect a solution for. The event nudged him from a shared home in the suburbs into the heart of San Francisco. He now resides in a minimalist apartment in Hayes Valley, a 2.1-mile Muni ride from his SoMa office. His routine is a cherished ritual: a pour-over from a local cafe, the rhythmic hum of the train, and evenings spent either at the gym, with a small circle of friends for board games, or simply reading by his large window overlooking the bustling street.\n\nThough professionally fulfilled, Mateo, at 48, yearns for a different kind of structure\u2014one of deeper personal connection and legacy. He\u2019s begun mentoring young Filipino-American students entering the tech field, a nod to the parents who sacrificed so much. His quiet aspiration is to one day apply his skills to a project with cultural significance, perhaps designing the digital archive for a Filipino-American historical society, bringing elegant order to the stories of his own community."
        },
