            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was ten, sitting on an overturned bucket in his father\u2019s Daly City garage. The air was thick with the scent of motor oil and the coastal fog. His father, hands stained but movements precise, wasn\u2019t just fixing a carburetor; he was restoring order. He pointed to the neatly arranged wrenches on the pegboard. \u201cEverything has a place, anak. A reason.\u201d In that quiet moment, watching his father transform chaos into a running engine, Mateo learned that structure wasn't confinement\u2014it was function, it was care.\n***\n2.\nIt was 1997, in the hushed halls of Berkeley\u2019s Doe Library. Surrounded by the logical comfort of the card catalog, Mateo sat at a terminal and experienced the early web. It was a beautiful, anarchic mess\u2014a universe of information with no system. While his classmates saw chaos, he saw a challenge. An overwhelming, thrilling sense of purpose washed over him. He wasn't abandoning the library; he was going to build a new and infinitely larger one, its shelves made of code instead of wood.\n***\n3.\nHis first night in the Hayes Valley apartment felt impossibly quiet. After the divorce, he\u2019d shed a house, a marriage, a life. He stood at the wall-sized window, watching the 21-Hayes bus groan past. There was no sense of failure, only a blank slate. He felt not like a man whose life had collapsed, but like an architect before an empty plot of land. For the first time, the system he had to design was his own happiness, and its core principle would be simplicity.\n***\n4.\nHe met his first mentee, a nervous Filipino-American coder, for coffee. She confessed feeling like a fraud. Mateo didn\u2019t offer platitudes. He described watching his mother, a caregiver, organize a patient\u2019s pillbox with such meticulous love, creating a system that sustained a life. \u201cOur parents built systems of survival with their hands,\u201d he told her. \u201cWe just do it with keyboards. The instinct is the same.\u201d In her nod of understanding, he felt a blueprint for a new kind of legacy click into place.\n***\n5.\nAt a Filipino-American Historical Society event, he saw a spread of faded, unlabeled photographs\u2014laborers in Stockton fields, families in South of Market. The stories felt immense but untethered. A profound ache bloomed in his chest, an ambition that had nothing to do with corporate data. He suddenly envisioned it: a digital archive, elegant and intuitive, where any child could find their grandfather\u2019s story. It would be the most important structure he had ever designed, an architecture of memory itself."
